<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2006-07-04a.34.2" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/lord/100559" speakername="Lord Sainsbury of Turville" colon=":" colnum="34"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds06/text/60704w0197.htm#06070470000088">
	<p pid="a.34.2/1">Copies of the DTI's final regulatory impact assessment on the restriction of hazardous substances directive were submitted to the Library of the House on <phrase class="date" code="2006-05-25">25 May</phrase> this year. The annualised costs to UK industry have been estimated to be between &pound;91 and &pound;170 million over the next 10 years. Delaying implementation would mean that equipment placed on the UK market would not have incurred their proportion of these costs but any equipment exported to other EU member states would have had to comply to be lawfully placed on the market in those countries. It would not have been economically feasible for companies placing goods on the EU market to run two manufacturing lines.</p>
</reply>
